<font color="#FF0000">THE VALUE OF TELLING THE TRUTH</font><br>
<tt>Fri Apr 18 21:48:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Lien, as usual, allow me a different point of view.  As the anti-war protestor of the 60's, most of my group were divided between ending/stopping the war (to save their own butts &amp; American soldiers), and making a moral claim.  What was happening to the &quot;locals&quot; was not an issue or even pause for thought until that photo of Kim Phuc.  That fed the &quot;moral righteousness&quot; of the left wing protest movement.  Sort of &quot;see, how horrible you guys are, this must stop&quot;. Never a thought, however, to what the Communists/North was doing to civilians (that was not trendy so was ignored).<br><br>
The war ended and the soldiers came back, and the peace/anti war movement folded.  The flood of refugee's came, and I believe a resentment grew. I know it did. They (the Vietnamese refugee's) were the children of America's mistake and as such, a reminder of the price &quot;we&quot; had to pay.  I know of much anti-Vietnamese sentiment then, and now.<br><br>
I have had to deal with it, both professionally and personally, and what I have found then, and now, is that many non-vets don't like Vietnamese. They feel they are here and should go home.  That is just the same as every other wave of immigrants that America has had, the Irish, Jews, East Europeans, Italians, etc., and all had the same backlash, based on fear and ignorance mostly.  So that anti-Vietnamese feeling is part of the assimilation process and therefore a natural American reaction.<br><br>
I live 45 minutes from Little Saigon.  To me that symbol, that sign of the freeway that announces: &quot;Little Saigon&quot;'s off ramp, bugs me.  It sets the community apart and stops the Americanization process.  My grandparents came to America, they learned English (the language of America) as fast as they could, changed their style of dress, and raised their kids as Americans.  They did not set up a Little Poland, or Little Odessa, instead, they sought to distance from it and become Americanized as fast as they could.  <br><br>
I do not support multi-culturalism in other words, and I think that along with political correct thinking, it is destroying the very country that I love.<br><br>
On the personal side, I have found that the definition of what is &quot;truth&quot; and what is a &quot;lie&quot; is quite different between the Vietnamese and American cultures.  Does that make me a racist? Or just someone noticing the difference? <br><br>
I think in a country torn apart by war from outsiders for several generations, truth becomes a commodity to be used to survive. In America, a land not so ravaged, we naively value &quot;truth&quot; perhaps too highly.  However, the end result of mixing the two cultures together is that one, or perhaps both, go away with the wrong impressions of each other.  <br><br>
I just know that when I see the Little Saigon sign, I don't like it.  Enjoy your culture, just like every other immigrant group has, but also, just like every other immigrant group had done, don't push it in my face. Don't force me to acknowledge your culture. If I choose to, I can, I just want to have the choice.<br><br>
It surprises me that I have this strong of a reaction, and when I talk with many vets of the Nam war, they seem to understand the people and culture more than I do.  Perhaps exposure creates knowledge, which I think I read in DocDel's<br>
post above. Tom Dier clearly is more advanced in his thinking than I am, because I can not echo his &quot;welcome home&quot; greeting.  Esp. to someone who signs off with no e mail address or name (your choice I know).  I guess it is that truth thing again, and how much a culture values &quot;truth&quot; over survival.  <br><br>
When you mention the newscast seemed resentful, that is because I suspect it was.  I hope I have helped you understand why that is.  Perhaps I am way off base, if so I will get my head handed to me.  Perhaps not.  But---this is only a post in cyberspace, and I can not respect someone who deliberately signs off as &quot;alias-lien&quot; with no address, be you red, white, pink, yellow, brown, black, or purple.<br><br>

